# Agentic SDLC — Core Operating Rules

This project uses the Agentic SDLC framework. The full rules live in `CLAUDE.md` (also read by Claude Code, same content). Below is the condensed version for Cursor.

## Non-Negotiable Rules

1. **Every change goes through OpenSpec:** proposal → design → specs → tasks → implement → archive. Never skip.
2. **Every task must include tests.** Commits without tests are blocked.
3. **Micro cycle:** Pick task → Implement → Write tests → Run tests → Commit if passing → Next.
4. **Small files, small commits.** Services < 150 lines, screens < 200 lines. One logical change per commit.
5. **Read memory before starting, write memory after completing.**
6. **Anti-patterns get named specifically** — "not modular" / "silent fallback to zero", not just "bad".
7. **Failures become core memories.** Record every mistake in the agent's memory so it doesn't repeat.

## Micro Cycle (every task)

1. Read task from `tasks/queue/<task-id>.json` (if using task queue) or user request.
2. Read agent memory: `node ~/agentic-sdlc/agents/memory-manager.mjs recall <agent>`.
3. Implement the change in the smallest reasonable scope.
4. Write tests (happy path + at least one error case).
5. Run the project's test command.
6. If frontend files changed → run browser E2E against a local production build.
7. If tests pass → commit → mark task complete. If they fail → fix and re-run (max 3 attempts, then flag blocked).
8. Append to `plans/devlog.md` with what changed.

## OpenSpec Commands (Cursor-friendly — no `/skill` system)

When the user asks for OpenSpec workflow actions, run the matching CLI:

| User says | Action |
|---|---|
| "start a new change" / "openspec new" | `openspec new change "<kebab-name>"` then `openspec instructions <first-artifact>` |
| "continue" / "next artifact" | `openspec list --json` → `openspec status --change "<name>" --json` → draft the next artifact |
| "fast forward" / "ff" | Loop all ready artifacts in dependency order |
| "implement" / "apply" | Read proposal + design + specs + tasks, then follow the micro cycle per task |
| "verify" / "check" | Grep codebase for each REQ-xxx, report CRITICAL / WARNING / SUGGESTION |
| "archive" / "done" | Move `openspec/changes/<name>` → `openspec/changes/archive/YYYY-MM-DD-<name>` |

Ask the user before jumping from one artifact to the next — don't speed-run the whole workflow unless they explicitly say "ff".

## Testing Tiers

```bash
<project-test-cmd>                                   # Tier 1: unit
<integration-cmd>                                    # Tier 2: service↔store
<defeat-cmd>                                         # Tier 3: anti-pattern scans
node ~/agentic-sdlc/agents/four-layer-validate.mjs   # 4-layer AST validation
node ~/agentic-sdlc/agents/test-behavior.mjs         # Agent prompt quality
# Tier 5 (browser E2E) when frontend touched
```

- After any code change: run full test suite.
- Before every commit: run defeat tests if configured.
- After editing any `AGENT.md`: run behavior tests — MUST pass before committing.

## Done Checklist (project.json configurable)

Default for app projects: `["openspec", "tests", "commit", "deploy", "verify", "notify"]`.
Default for framework repos: `["openspec", "tests", "commit", "push"]`.

"Wrote the code" is NOT "shipped the fix." Every step in the project's configured list must complete before reporting done.

